Introduction
We see that when we try to express the distribution of the planets in terms of Euler’s number (e)
and the golden ratio conjugate (phi), the scheme suggests that the planets are doing what I call
a weird calculus. It is where the derivative of the exponential e to the x is not itself, as it is in
regular calculus, as arises from the conundrum of trying to take the integral of 1/x. But rather
follows suit with . We further see that the planets in terms of e and phi,
quantize in terms of whole numbers in suit with digital binary used in artiﬁcial intelligence logic
circuitry. With the suggestion of a weird calculus we suggest the existence of a weird
arithmetic, which we ﬁnd when compared to regular arithmetic and expanded with a Taylor
series creates terms which accurately describe the distribution of the planets as well if we
compare the regular arithmetic to the weird arithmetic. "

from the argument, that the ﬁrst planet being the closest to the Sun, sets the idea in motion, that idea being

the one planets in the solar system that is highly hospitable to life.

does not work we go the next simplest expression r(n)=2n. Seeing this does not work we go one step
higher in complexity and try . We see this does not work either so we go one step of complexity

The nebulae are relatively dense regions in the interstellar medium the densest of which are nebulae or
clouds of about 10,000 molecules per cubic centimeter. In our calculation we are dealing with
5E8/2=2.5E8 H2 molecules=250,000,000. The air we breathe is about 1E19 molecules per cc. The radius
of Jupiter is 11.3 earth radii and it has a mass of 317 earth-masses. 90% of this is hydrogen and 9% is
helium. The mean density of Jupiter is 1.3 g/cc.
But most of this is less dense H_2 in the atmosphere and it turns into the metallic state at depths of 10,000
km. For 250,000,0000 H2 molecules per cc that is 6.711E-16 g\cc of H2.
Aurigae seems to be a F-type supergiant orbited by a B5V star at the center of an edge-on disk that
eclipses the star every 27 years for a duration of about 2 years. A B5V star would have a mass of 5.9 solar
masses. For a fairly normal orbit around a F-type supergiant for the primary requires a secondary with a
mass of over 13 solar masses. The disc around the secondary star is 10AU wide and 0.9AU thick and
block about 70% of the light that passes through it from the primary and radiates like a 550K black body.
The star is thought to be at 1,350+/-350 ly from Earth.
R=748,000,000 AU
h=134,640,000 AU
As a right circular cylinder that is a volume of
2.3666E26 cubic km
Compare this to the density we were speaking about from the Venus circuit: 6.7E-16g/cc. It is 90,000
times more dense which works because the density will be greater near the center and lower as one moves
out towards the edge. The secondary in epsilon Aur is a small disk, larger disks with a primary at the
center will be much less dense if computed in the same way.
